Date:  0/0/1923
Source:  NZ Journal of Science & Technology
Author:
Vol / Page:  6/87
Edition:
Quote:  <i>Acanthisitta chloris</i> Sparr. Rifleman. Owing to the uncertainty regarding the species denoted by the term `wren' as used by the average observer, many records which may apply to this species have been left strictly alone. In the Wellington District the grey warbler  (<i>Maorigerygone igata</i> Quoy & Gaim.) is often referred to in popular parlance as the `native wren.'
Notes:  Myers Endemic Birds

Date:  0/0/1947
Source:  Native Animals of NZ
Author:  POWELL
Vol / Page:  86
Edition:
Quote:  RIFLEMAN (<i>Acanthisitta chloris</i>). This is a wren and our smallest bird, being only three inches in total length. There are two forms, typical chloris from the South Island and <i>A. chloris granti</i>, the North Island rifleman....The Maori name is Titi-pounamu.
